I am a farmer of worms, but I am also the worms, and I am also the soil, the sun, the rot, the process of rotting, and all of the icebergs in the cold seas of north.

I feel like a rare breed of spider, like the cloths of a mummy in the sand of Egypt, like all the protons of all the stars in the galaxies, like a solar storm upon the sun's southern plasma-continents. I feel like you, brother!

I still think how my priest told me that in some churches deep in Africa, they celebrate Easter after the end of the dry season/Harmatan, when the green returns to the lands and nature blooms again. It is a very beautiful and romantic thing.

I am often reminded of how Chesterton (PBUH) correctly diagnosed that many of his religious brothers are incorrectly scared of sex, when it is not sex that is bad, but only lust. Nature is incredibly sexual - the singing of birds, battles of elk - and yet it is holy, is it not?

Of course, nature is also and fallen - but is its sexuality a part of its primordial decadence? At times I have went as far as to suspect the very shape, and nature, and substance, and every aspect of all is blasphemous - that trees should be spheres, not trees - but this's wrong
